      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "There is no fixed minimum. All-program draw cutoffs in 2025–2026 ranged from 470 to 525. French-language draws can be as low as 300–380. Category draws range from 430 to 490." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is 400 a good CRS score for Canada PR?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "400 is generally not competitive for all-program draws (cutoff ~470–525), but may qualify for French-language draws, category draws, or PNP streams. A PNP nomination adds +600 CRS points, making 400 a total of 1,000 — well above any draw cutoff." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is 450 CRS score enough for Canada PR?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "450 is below recent all-program draw cutoffs (~470–525) but may qualify for category-based draws (healthcare, trades, agriculture typically 430–475) or a provincial nomination." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a good CRS score for Canada PR?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A score above 490 is competitive for most Express Entry draw types. Above 520 is strong for all-program draws. Below 480, targeting a PNP or category-based draw is the recommended strategy." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does a PNP nomination affect CRS score for Canada PR?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A provincial nomination through an Enhanced PNP stream adds exactly +600 CRS points, virtually guaranteeing an ITA at the next PNP-only draw regardless of your base score." }
    },
